text: People should really stop judging the movie before they see it, especially based off of the trailer. Movie trailers nowadays are like mini-films themselves. They're created by companies completely separate from the production team of the film itself. An entirely different group of people that weren't involved with the making of the film receive a rough copy of a movie and have to think of a way to present it to captivate the widest possible audience. They use many tactics to do this, and a lot of what goes into movie trailer production is a manipulation of the actual film itself. Scenes play out and are edited differently in trailers than in the actual film many times. So stop being so judgmental and wait for the actual film to come out before you say anything. And if you KNOW you're not going to see the film, why are you taking the time out of your day to post about it and be so negative instead of doing something else with your time? Are your comments even productive? There's a difference between giving and honest, constructive opinion of a film and simply saying "this looks awful lol" or "this will FLOP". At the very least elaborate, or don't speak!

text: Guys. I want share a story I had with an Ouiji board. It was the thing in my life that gave me a lot of pain.  When I was 11 years old (I'm 25 now), my enemy was my grandmother: Nana Dumpling.   She told me to hide myself in my parents room till I learned how to breathe less.   So I went to their room, and opened my mother's panty drawer. They smelled like Downy. :3 mmmmm. *drools*  And I found a note in the deep end of the top drawer and it said "don't look in the attic."   I obviously went to the attic because I thought the note was referring to candy. I went up there and found a box. I went through it and found an Ouiji board. Under it was vhs tape that said "mom's secret affair" but I didn't pay much attention to it.   So I took the board and violated Nana rules and told her what I found. She picked it up and started hitting me with it. It hurt like a bitch. She hit my face and spanked my ass with it.  So I warn you guys. Beware, because an Ouiji board can hurt you.Ôªø

text: So here we have another instance of careless business men cashing in on a name that should not have even had the opportunity, nor the right, to be translated into film to begin with. Not only did they do it once, but now they're gonna make a sequel everybody! I don't understand how a human being can be genuinely interested in watching a movie that is based on a FUCKING BOARD GAME. It's not scary. It's not compelling. It's not interesting. It's not different. It's cheap, it's lazy, it's pathetic, and to be frank, it's a disgrace, and is a perfect example of what is wrong with the film industry in this day in age. We've reached a point in time in which creativity is so scarce, that filmmakers are resorting to using fucking board games you play with your family on a boring ass Sunday night, as a foundation behind what their inspiration is for making a film. The first piece of shit board game Ouija film made $103 million dollars because of the fact that uneducated, dimwitted, teenagers who are scared of loud noises and a piece of cardboard on the ground, paid their parents' money to go see a film that was designated exactly for the fools who were moronic enough to shell out money to see something as ridiculous as this. They've created this sequel, not because the first broke barriers; not because it brought a new style to the art of film; not because it was graced with oscar worthy performances. But because it made MONEY. If you honestly have any sort of dignity, any sort of awareness of what genuine, quality, creative, and innovative film is, don't see this movie. Please. For the love of all that is holy, just fucking don't.
author: AlphaPhatFilms

text: Can we please take a moment to appreciate that the Ouija Board is the most overused and cliche horror plot device? As such, with how much attention this movie is getting, I have VERY high expectations of the rest of the story. The mood is already by said plot device, so they better have some damn good spoops and hopefully don't rely too heavily on jump scares. A jump scare here and there is okay, especially when it turns out to be nothing. That keeps the viewer on their toes. But if it's everywhere (Like SOME movies and games that I know. Everyone throw in some name btw) it gets REALLY boring after the first few "scares".

This movie has a strong plot, believable characters and fine performances, which is all the recent horror movies lack. I hope they make another one with the same director. I dare say this is the best thing that happened to the supernatural horror genre since Exorcist.

text: Satan and his demons can use the Ouija board to give advice, or even to guide a person in a certain direction. This guidance may even seem to be true, good, and helpful. Satan and his demons pretend to be caring. They try to appear as something that appears harmless. The Bible says, "And no wonder, for Satan himself masquerades as an angel of light. It is not surprising, then, if his servants masquerade as servants of righteousness. Their end will be what their actions deserve" (2 Corinthians 11:14-15).   Satan and his demons will do this in order to get a person even more deeply involved in spiritist practices. Things like the Ouija board appear to be innocent at first, but soon a person finds themselves addicted to guidance from the spirit world - thereby allowing Satan to control and destroy their life. 1 Peter 5:8 warns us, "Be self-controlled and alert. Your enemy the devil prowls around like a roaring lion looking for someone to devour."   The Ouija Board may be advertised as just as game, and that is exactly what Satan wants us to believe. Sadly, many people are deceived into believing that Ouija Boards ARE just a game. The truth of the matter is that God views channeling, or consulting spirits or the dead, to be a serious sin.

text: Watch your ears, there is apparently ZERO compression on these audio tracks.  The jump scares are EXTREMELY LOUD. I find that and jump scares annoying by themselves. I think it's a lazy way to make a movie.   Ok, so the mother's a scam artist. Then she runs across the ouija board and all hell breaks loose. The "spirits" give them an answer posed by the mother that no one knew but her, she jumps,  and the daughter says, "Is she right?"   Duh.   Slight spoilers to end:    If the planchette thing moves all around on it's own, without anyone touching it, why is no one REALLY disconcerted by that?   or the daughter writing Polish? And how's she even know what Polish looks like??   Why wasn't the boy VERY disconcerted at the girls description of being choked to death? I'd've been *gone* long before she finished the monologue (backs away).   Some of the stunts were very cool, NOT green screen, and I must start 10 movies from the library to every one I finish. I give it five minutes to do or say something interesting. That's not asking too much for tens or hundreds of millions of dollars to make a movie, I don't think.    Out of 10, I'll give it a 7.5. I wasn't bored and I liked the sets.
